< review>
I've been here quite a bit for crown work with Dr. Moeller, and he and his staff have been really great in managing my case and following up on my overall dental health to make sure I was doing well. The front desk staff were also always helpful and polite, like helping me modify my treatment plan when I got a referral to an endodontist for a fused molar root canal.

Besides the compassionate treatment I've been given, this office also provides emergency dental care - I was seen on short notice for a broken temporary with no hassle. There can be some times where you can wait a bit to be seen, but if you're waiting it's likely because you're either there on Saturday (it gets busy!) or there's someone in an emergency in front of you.

And if you're complaining about the cost.... dental care is expensive pretty much everywhere, even with insurance! I got great care and I'll come back for more great care again.</review>

Zero stars. CLEAN YOUR DOOR. (it's probably still unsightly dirty) I wanted to utilize my medi-cal coverage since I got off my other insurance.
Most horrifying experience at a dentist. I went in for a cleaning as a new patient.. 2 people in there, took 2.5 hours to get x-rays done -ok whatever. The dentist lady, was the least compassionate person, didn't say anything to me for about 5 minutes as she stood there, told me I had 2 cavities, and needed a root canal. I had been very stressed the month prior recovering a torn meniscus, so it reflected in my teeth. Made me feel extremely uncomfortable. I scheduled a cleaning for the next day despite the weird feeling everyone gave me, they pushed a filling, which I scheduled but backed out of last minute. The next day for my cleaning they seemed to be mad that I made the decision to back out of the filling, even after telling them I had a motocross race the next day and I didn't feel okay with having tender teeth for, since I clench. Long story short, the dentist said nothing to me during the cleaning, clearly mad, the assistant literally choked me with the spit sucker. She grinded my teeth in all of about 2 minutes which hurt like hell, didn't try to avoid my gums. I was squirming and she never asked if I was alright. When she finished she just walked away and didn't say anything leaving the assistant with me. I literally shed a tear because I couldn't breathe with the spit sucker down my throat, and I even gagged a couple times. After that, the assistant put thick fluoride gel on my teeth, which I don't use fluoride because it's TOXIC and I'm allergic and sensitive to chemicals. It's been about a month and she grinded my back tooth into a sharp edge which has caused me pain and more problems. Since the fluoride treatment, my gums have been hurting and my teeth are ultra sensitive. I had to call my old dentist, and will gladly pay the fee to see them. They are even giving me a discount after hearing about my experience with these quacks. Please don't bring your children here. This place is unprofessional and dirty.
Show some compassion to your patients! Though, I will never come back here again. It wasn't worth a free cleaning from my insurance. :(< /text>

<Review>I must‚Äôve driven past this place a thousand times and never even realized it was here. So glad I got off the freeway are ran into this place. They have such a wide range of inventory, it‚Äôs easy to get caught up in one area and miss an entire section of this huge warehouse. And, it‚Äôs actually two shops next door to each other. The larger of the two houses mostly large furniture, decor and hardware items. All of it is super well made. Just looking at each piece, you can see the history and the stories it tells.

<time>1500907142983</time>< Review>
Honest, professional and thorough.     R&S has been our go to mechanic for over 10 years. And I have no reason to change.

Their quality is top notch  and they standyby their work.      But the most impressive part is their integrity.

Two examples:    I had some work done to my van.   It was rather extensive and the price tag reflected it.    The following day, I get a call from Eddie, the owner.   He said that he reviewed the bill and found that some of the work was covered by their warranty   "Where would you like the refined chris eck mailed for the $500".

Second example happend just last week.   My Sedans power steering went out.     I have them check and it needs a new pump.    But instead of the $300 charge to replace it, Mario, their awesome service advisor, tells me that Chevy has a service advisory on it, and if i take it to them, they will replace it free.    Who does that?!!    They could have made $300 and I would have been none the wiser.

That's why I take all my cars and highly recommend R&S Automotive.< /Review>

< user_name>
Marcus Rigsby< /user_name>
<Time>1410546971819</Time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
I switched to R&S on an enthusiastic recommendation from a family friend. I became suspicious of my old mechanic when he slapped me with over $700 in maintenance and repairs on a drastically over-priced used car he'd sold me. Up to that point I'd only racked up 2100 miles on it. When I brought it to R&S to fix a coolant leak, they identified the problem as a leaky hose and stuck thermostat, and didn't try to add on any suspicious or arbitrary services. They charged me $75 less than their original estimate.

They also carted me back and forth twice between Newhall and Canyon Country at no extra cost. Everyone I met was friendly and approachable and patient with my questions. As far as I am able to judge, R&S is a fair, honest, and efficient mechanic, and for me, that is everything.< /review>

The paper stated very clearly that this charge was OPTIONAL and was NOT required to buy the vehicle. I asked more than three times for it to be removed and the finance department wouldn't budge, saying it was "to protect cars from being stolen from the lot". They said initially they would do a full diagnostic of the engine/breaks/etc. which would cost $129, but be applied to the cost of any repairs needed. No drama during the whole process. I highly recommend this dealership.< /Review>

Good selection. Pleasant sales staff. Good deals. Fair trade in on our high mileage Forester. We recommend asking for Rocky if you want a very nice, helpful salesman. No high pressure sales games experienced at this dealership. Very happy with our 2017 Forester. Drove a manual transmission Subaru since 1984 and was skeptical about the CVT automatic for all the mountain driving we do. If you live at high altitude where winters are cold, do yourself a favor and go for the winter package as we have for the last four or five Subaru purchases. < review>
Got our 2017 Subaru Forester here about a year ago.  Their free service for 3 yrs was a great sweetening deal compared to other Subaru dealers in the surrounding areas. And it just so happened one Forester with the exact features we wanted had been delivered that day and had only 4 miles on it.
We knew what we wanted so didn‚Äôt have any lengthy sales process - just got right to it.
It was almost closing time when we arrived- probably 9 or 930pm and the staff stayed and helped us without any pressure about closing time.
I had originally planned to buy outright, but the manager encouraged us to lease since we would be using primarily for business purposes and the entire lease is deductible.  The buyout value at the end of the lease would also be lower than resale value if we took good care of it, so that meant also meant we‚Äôd get a credit towards a future one.  This was great advice and council for us and we‚Äôre glad we did lease.
It was about midnight by the time the paperwork was done and we could drive off and the staff were great the entire time.
They gave us a $50 gas card if we would return a different day for new owner training, and we obliged.

We found when we got home that the protective cargo tray mat in the back was defective and too small for the space.  We also noticed a few scuff marks inside on the fabric.
When we went back in for new owner training, they cleaned up the scuff marks for us and even though they‚Äôd never seen this mat issue before and were quite baffled by it, they found us a replacement that fit. They also found 2 other defective ones in the process but stuck with it until they got us a proper one.

When we purchased I was skeptical about the service as I‚Äôd read so many negative reviews here, but I‚Äôve now had 2 official service appts and have been very satisfied with them.
The online scheduler did not seem to work right, so I call and schedule by phone.
They‚Äôve gotten my car in promptly both times and had it ready within an hour.

I had a tiny paint touch up that was needed and they put it on for me.
Most all of the staff have been kind, pleasant, and very approachable, and on the rare occasion I first get someone who isn‚Äôt knowledgeable in what I need they quickly find me someone who is.

We‚Äôve put 12000 miles on the car in a year and love it!

The only problems I‚Äôve experienced are these:
The sales guy told me he‚Äôd call me to schedule the new car training, but he never did.  I had to call in and was basically told to just come in whenever was good for me.  So I did and all was fine.

When I ordered the touch up paint, they never called to tell me it had arrived.  I called and checked a few weeks later and it was there on hold for me.

Overall I‚Äôve had very positive experiences and highly recommend this dealer!< /review>

The reason for 1 star is once you have purchased from them, their service is absolutely horrible.  They do not care about their customers. I bought my Subaru in August, 2018,  financing with Subaru of Ontario and buying additional packages, due to how great they said they would service you.
So my problem:
I have contacted them 6 times to get a simple question answered. Nobody can be bothered contacting me. 1st time no answer, 2nd time left message for Business Manager, 3rd time went through online chat left my email and phone #,  4th  and 5th times left voice messages for the service department. 6th time (day 4) Called roadside assistance department - and guess what they go home at 5 p.m.
I have a cracked windshield I have called 4 days in a row to get a simple answer - A. With the extra packages we purchased with the Subaru is the windshield covered (we paid like $3000.00 for several different extra programs.) B. If not, what is the price for getting it replaced. I don't want to schedule service for an amount that I don't know. Without a quote I am at the mercy of the dealer setting any price they want.
In comparison I was to able to get a quote from every other window replacement company, actually received four within 30 minutes from Yelp, and then two additional ones from larger glass companies on their websites. However, the people I paid $35,000.00 to that promised the world with the purchase cannot be bothered to take 5 minutes to respond.
Secondary issue that I would not have commented on publically, but since I am here - We had a recall which we scheduled an appointment for. I turned up 10 minutes prior to my appointment. It took 30 minutes after my actual appointment time to check in. Now the service at that point of check in, getting the car taken care of and pick-up was good. However, as a customer coming in  because of a manufacturer defect, a 30 minute wait for a scheduled appointment ,again shows the absolute lack of respect for their customers. My time is also valuable. I had someone else waiting on me, we had plans scheduled - based on a promised time that was not honored which we almost missed. Highly unacceptable.
My advice - do not buy a car here. They have zero ability to be helpful.</text>

<name>Nick Barge</name><review>I am dropping my review from 5 stars, down to one. Once the car was sold to me, the service department began to SERIOUSLY drop the ball. at 3,000 miles, my brand new Impreza had a low oil light. No one cared. At 6,000 miles, the low light came on, again, and I was told "The car was probably under filled from the manufacture, low oil is normal." Being naive and thinking hey, I just bought one of the highest rated cars from a brand known to take care of the owners, I let it go. at 9,000 miles, the low oil light came on AGAIN. The dealer finally began an oil consumption analysis and discovered the car was 1.4 quarts low, scolded me for checking the oil myself (they mark the oil dipstick with RTV to see if you have checked it) DESPITE living 30 miles away. If the car would have been out of oil and I would have driven it in, I'm sure they would have made me out of pocket the cost of an engine.  at 12,000 miles, the low oil lamp came back on predictably. I checked the oil... and took the car in. I was then told that the car wasn't consuming out of limits, as the service rep insisted there is only 10 ounces in a quart. After telling him no there is more than 10 ounces in a quart, They admitted it failed topped off the oil and told me to come back once the light came on again... instead of doing something about it... on the 4th reported instance of this happening... I was out of time and exhausted so I went home, stewed on it over night, and returned the car the next day insisting that I get the new engine that the paperwork they gave me says I was entitled to and that I get comped a rental. They did finally say ok, we will put you in a rental and replace the engine. I wish it ended at that.

After about a week in the rental, of which the car its self I have no complaints about, I was rear ended in a hit and run. Obviously no fault of the dealer in any way, life happens. Rear bumper was crunched up and muffler was dented pretty bad. I inform the dealer and my insurance, that all goes over well, until I request a new loaner, as I am making payments to drive a new car, and if I was hit in my personal vehicle I'd be placed in a similar new and un damaged rental to drive until the repairs are done, I reasonably expected one. No response. I called for several days and left a lot of voicemails with the service manager. no response. I mean, not a deal breaker, especially seeing as at this point I thought it might only be a few more days until I got my car back.

Nope.

It took 36 days to replace the engine on my Subaru. I was told "It'll be done by friday!" THREE times. Then it took over 2 hours to receive my car once they told me it was done, and I even waited until the next day! I arrived to a car that hadn't been washed and was rushed to sign paperwork before I even SAW the car. So they hurry up, wash it, I insist on at least giving the car a once over and at the surface it all looks ok, finally. THEN I waited another 45 minutes for the car porter to get off break, I couldn't even get my stuff out of the loaner as he TOOK THE KEYS BEFORE HE LEFT. Once he got back he was constantly rushing me and telling me how much work he had to do. If he would have SIMPLY LEFT THE KEYS I WOULD HAVE ALREADY MOVED EVERYTHING!

I drive the car home, all seems fine and happy. FINALLY, I have the car back and it hopefully won't have any more issues.

Then a week later the blower motor starts chirping at any fan speed, and the car begins bucking when under load in first gear, which as anyone else who lives in the San Bernardino Mtns and drives a stick shift will tell you... you spend a lot of time climbing hills in first gear. At this point, I'm loaded with work and don't have time to stop and waste 3 hours. So I called. Every day. For over a week. Leave a voice mail with either service or the service manager, with NO response. At one point I heard the phone get picked up then promptly disconnected.

This is hands down the WORST customer service I have ever experienced, and I would advise anyone to go to LITERALLY ANY OTHER subaru dealer in SoCal.<//review>< pictures>

< text>
Well it finally happened. I had heard rumors of Subaru dealerships requiring credit applications BEFORE test driving and this is one of those dealerships. I honestly could accept the credit application requirement for test driving an STi,  but they also required an application for the WRX! Absolutely ridiculous.

I came in today to do my research ahead of the termination of my current lease, which expires in March. I have several cars on the list and have worked my way through almost all of them. Every salesman I have met has been courteous and very understanding of my research. Today I was met with hostility for the first time ever. I have driven Alfa Romeo, VW, BMW, Audi, Honda, Dodge, Ford, Mercedes-Benz and none of them cared. Half of them didn't even require a drivers license to be turned over before the test drive. I gladly turned over any personal information they needed, except for SSN, and was very open with them.

I have never been asked to provide a credit application before driving a car until today. The salesman did not introduce himself, did not ask my name or my partners name. He had no knowledge of his inventory. We walked around looking at stickers to figure out which was a base model WRX. Finally we found one. The right color, right basic options (I'm a no frills guy, not cheap) and a manual. I'm ready for a test drive. After 30 minutes of jerking around I get hit with the credit application bull. We tested the back seat space and left. I am so dejected.

I will go to Carmax to test drive both the STi and WRX where they are happy to have people come in. And if I like them over my current front runners, I will probably buy from them. Their bumper to bumper warranty is better anyways.< /text>

< review>
My experience with Subaru of Ontario started off well but ended badly. Hopefully this review can save you some trouble if you're considering a purchase from this dealer.

I sent an online inquiry from one of the car pricing websites and received a response from an internet salesperson at the dealership. We corresponded about pricing and options and she informed me she had two cars in stock, one black and one dark gray. The following is the actual email I sent to her confirming the quote (I've blocked out the pricing):

"Also, just so I understand, the quote would be as follows: Legacy 2.5i Premium PZEV = $xxx, Eyesight + Blind Spot Detection & Rear Cross Traffic Alert = $xxx, Leather Seating = $xxx, Total = $xxx."

The following is the actual email response she sent back to me (I've blocked out the pricing):

"The price you suggested below is correct according to the email quotes that are sent out. The only thing that it does not include which I always mention to my customers is the destination charge of $xxx. So it would be $xxx for the vehicle itself + $xxx for destination = $xxx + $xxx Eyesight, Blind Spot, Rear Traffic+ $xxx for leather = $xxx before taxes and fees."

I told her I was happy with the quote and that I'd take the black car. When I showed up to the dealer, the car they had waiting for me had navigation, moon roof, something called rear bumper applique, and a few other options that I wasn't told about, didn't ask for, didn't want, and increased the price significantly. When I pointed it out, they told me I misunderstood the quote. So I pulled up the email chain above. Then they tried to offer me a different car in a different color that I didn't want. When I refused that...surprise, surprise...the sales manager came out. We went around and around and he finally came to the point where he just flat out told me the quote was a mistake and he wouldn't honor it. He was rude and unapologetic about it as well.

Do I think this was really a "mistake"? I have no way of knowing for sure, but I did a google search on "car dealer bait and switch" and thought I was reading a recap. I've drawn my own conclusion; you can draw yours.

I wish I could direct you to Honest and Ethical Car Dealer X, but I can't. What I can do is save you a trip. If you live in LA and are considering making a trip to this dealer because they offered you a straight-forward, hassle-free quote--what you actually get may turn out to be neither of those things. Stay closer to home. You'll probably still have to deal with shady sales tactics, but at least you won't be subjecting yourself to a few extra hours in traffic to do so.</review>

<Review>This review is for my internet car-buying experience (so far; note that I'm waiting for the delivery and I have not yet been to their physical location).

I used their "contact us" form on the website to request a quote for a built-to-spec 2018 Crosstrek (I'd already test-driven the car and knew which options I wanted). Vince Sperling responded quickly with a competitive quote for the exact build I requested, no nonsense about "you should come in" or "we can't give out quotes online" or "how about this sorta similar vehicle we have on the lot" or "please call so we can work out the details". He followed up the email with a quick friendly call to make sure I had his quote and it was for what I wanted. I later got a slightly better quote, but Vince matched it. Eventually, based on his quote and the great experience I'd had interacting with Vince, I've decided to go through with the purchase with Vince and Subaru of Ontario over a similar quote from a different dealership.

Note that I contacted 14 LA area Subaru dealerships for this purchase. Most of them were pretty bad - quite a few were awful. Getting quotes was like pulling teeth. So Vince's help here, getting me the quote I asked for, being responsive, not pressuring me into something I don't want, being honest and straight-forward -- as "customer service 101" as that sounds, it really is exceptional in this business.

The car is expected to be delivered in October, and I'm anticipating the rest of this purchase will go smoothly, with the same no-nonsense no-hassle no-pressure experience I've had so far. I look forward to picking up my new Crosstrek. :)< /Review></record></dataset><record>

<text>The service on my Subaru was taken care of within an hour and I have no complaints with how either myself or my vehicle were treated.

I have chosen to give four rather than five stars because I witnessed some rather unprofessional behavior while I was there.  Two different employees, on a couple of occasions within my hour visit, sat (rested their behind on the hood/bumper) on the hood of an unsold STi.

I don't believe that they caused any real damage to the vehicle, although any contact with a painted surface that is not spotless or otherwise lubricated with some sort of cleaner/soapy water can cause swirl marks (fine scratches in the clear coat).

The real issue for me is that this kind of behavior symbolizes a certain lack of respect for what will eventually be a very significant piece of property for someone else.  The kind of person who buys an STi likely loves cars and driving, and wouldn't like the idea that their vehicle was sat on by anyone.

I realize that we aren't talking about a Ferrari or a Cadillac here, but as I said earlier, it simply seemed disrespectful to me.

Ultimately if the staff think that sitting on what is soon to be someone else's property is acceptable, I have to wonder what else they believe is within the realm of good behavior.

I called this dealer immediately to let them know what happened luckly the lady who helped me in the morning was still there. I told her what had happened & she told to drive it in. I asked her if they could tow it in she said no she did tell me that I can call for a tow but I would have to pay for it. I asked for the subaru road side assistance number and she gave it to me and then she told me she was leaving for the day but to just leave my car at the dealer and she would leave instructions with her team as to what happen.
